# =============================================================================
# Permoney Environment Variables — Template
# =============================================================================
# Copy this file to `.env` and fill in real values. NEVER commit `.env`.
#
# Loading: Prisma does NOT auto-load .env. The project uses `prisma.config.ts`
# which calls `import "dotenv/config"` to bridge env vars into the Prisma CLI.
# Application runtime (Vite+) auto-loads .env via Vite's standard mechanism.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Database (REQUIRED) — see ADR-0003 (docs/adr/0003-production-database.md)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Postgres connection string consumed by both:
#   1. Prisma CLI (migrations, generate) via prisma.config.ts
#   2. Runtime adapter `@prisma/adapter-pg` in src/server/db.server.ts
#
# `db.server.ts` validates the URL scheme at BOOT — anything that isn't
# `postgres://` or `postgresql://` (e.g. a leftover `file:` SQLite URL or
# `libsql://` Turso URL from a previous setup) crashes with a precise,
# actionable error. Failing fast > opaque error on first query.
#
# ── Local development (Docker Compose, see docker-compose.yml) ───────────────
# Bring the local DB up once with: `vp run db:up`
# Container exposes Postgres 16 on host port 5433 (NOT 5432, to avoid
# colliding with a system-installed Postgres on the same machine).
DATABASE_URL="postgres://permoney:permoney@localhost:5433/permoney"
#
# ── Production (managed Postgres: Neon / Supabase / RDS / etc.) ──────────────
# All managed providers require TLS — append `?sslmode=require` (or
# `?sslmode=verify-full` with a CA bundle) to the URL.
#
#   Neon:     postgres://<user>:<pw>@ep-<id>.<region>.aws.neon.tech/<db>?sslmode=require
#   Supabase: postgres://<user>:<pw>@db.<ref>.supabase.co:5432/postgres?sslmode=require
#
# DATABASE_URL="postgres://USER:PW@HOST:5432/DB?sslmode=require"

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Seed: privileged system-data URL — see ADR-0014
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The seed runs in two phases (PER-110 / ADR-0014):
#   1. Privileged system-data phase writes GLOBAL system categories
#      (isSystem = true, familyId IS NULL). After PER-102's RLS hardening this
#      requires a role that is a MEMBER of `permoney_system_maintainer` (the
#      role-targeted maintenance policy created by migration
#      20260530140000_category_system_maintenance_role). It does NOT require
#      BYPASSRLS.
#   2. App-tenant phase writes the demo tenant fixture through the regular
#      runtime app role using DATABASE_URL — no privileged access.
#
# Local dev: leave this UNSET. The local `permoney` role is superuser, and the
# migration grants `permoney_system_maintainer` to the migration runner, so the
# privileged phase falls back to DATABASE_URL and works as-is.
#
# Managed-Postgres production deploy contract:
#   - The role that runs `prisma migrate deploy` must either have CREATEROLE
#     (so the migration can `CREATE ROLE permoney_system_maintainer`) OR the
#     platform must pre-create that role and grant it to the migration runner.
#     The migration's IF NOT EXISTS guard makes the pre-created case a no-op.
#   - Set PERMONEY_SEED_PRIVILEGED_DATABASE_URL to a connection whose role is a
#     member of `permoney_system_maintainer`. If migrations and seed run under
#     the same privileged role, that role is already a member (the migration
#     grants it to CURRENT_USER) and this var can stay unset.
#   - The runtime app role behind DATABASE_URL must NOT be a member of
#     `permoney_system_maintainer`.
# PERMONEY_SEED_PRIVILEGED_DATABASE_URL="postgres://SEED_ROLE:PW@HOST:5432/DB?sslmode=require"

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Auth (FUTURE — not yet wired, see ADRs)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AUTH_SECRET="<openssl rand -base64 32>"
# AUTH_TRUST_HOST=true

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Observability (FUTURE)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SENTRY_DSN=""
# SENTRY_ENVIRONMENT="development"
